Grammy nominations: Michael Daugherty, Steve Mackey lead in the classical categories 
The classical nominations for the 53rd Grammy Award include a diverse mix of musicians and composers from around the world. 
Leading the list of Michael Daugherty's "Deux Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five votes, and Steve Mackey's "Dream House," an eclectic orchestral work, with three votes. 
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is the Estonian composer Arvo Pärt and his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles." This piece was from the Los Angeles Philharmonic commissioned and premiered in 2009 at Walt Disney Concert Hall. 
The LA-based composer Avner Dorman has been nominated for his mandolin Concert. 
Classical nominations are divided into 13 categories, ranging from orchestral, opera, choral to solo recordings. 
In the category of classical music producers have been nominated this year, five artists - Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson. 
Among the nominated classic albums are Bruckner's Symphonies Nos. 3 and 4 from the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" performed by the Nashville Symphony Orchestra, Steven Mackey's "Dream House" by the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" performed by various artists, and Verdi's "Requiem" by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus. 
In the opera category were Berg's "Lulu by the orchestra of the Royal Opera House; Adolf Hasse" Marc Antonio e Cleopatra "by Ars Lyrica Houston, Kaija Saariaho's" L'Amour de Loin "by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin's The Enchanted Wanderer" by the orchestra and chorus of the Mariinsky Theatre, and Arthur Sullivan's "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales nominated. 
As for composers Pärt's Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," Hans Werner Henze nominated for "Appassionatamente Plus, Magnus Lindberg for" Graffiti "and Shchedrin for" The Enchanted Wanderer "for a Grammy. 
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 on 4 January at the Disney Hall by the LA Philharmonic under Esa-Pekka Salonen premiered and recorded. 
The 30-minute piece is titled "Los Angeles" and is the former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky gewidmen who sits in jail in Russia. 
Dorman's "Mondo Concert Line" was nominated in the category of instrumental solo with orchestra. 
The composer from Los Angeles claimed to have the 15-minute piece written specifically for the mandolin artist Avi Avital, of the concert with the New York Metropolis Ensemble performed. 
"I've used sounds from the Middle East and many North African sounds and rhythms," Dorman said in a telephone interview. 
The conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination for orchestral performance for a recording of the works of Stravinsky with the Chicago Symphony Orchestra under his direction. 
As instrumental soloists, the pianist Nelson Freire and Marc-Andre Hamelin, the organist Paul Jacobs, the violinist Julia Fischer and the harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson have been nominated. 
As a vocal soloist in this year, only women were nominated, including Anne Sofie von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchoňová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman. 
In the category of classical crossover soprano Jessye Norman for their inclusion was "Roots - My Life, My Song" nomination. 
